&quot;However, I don&#39;t want to inject a lot of parameters in the Photography constructor just to make the class testable.&quot;

Being **testable** is a good quality of any piece of code. But more so you are **decoupling** responsibility and making the code more maintainable by associating hashing with the hashing generator. 

Also this now means u can independently test hashing without the class Photography. Its now **unit** testable hashing given a path for example without involving Photography

You should give everything **that you need to change** from outside[**context independence**] (giving at creation using a constructor or using a setter method. When you use the setting method, you should provide a default instance at constructor(not through parameters)) --- **Dependencies**(objects without which the constructed object do not makes sense) **should be provided through constructor.** Others could be given through setters.

NOTE: If you have to give too much helper object at constructor, then probably there are too much responsibility for the object. You should consider changing the design. (I think more than 8,9 parameter at constructor requires a redesign thinking)

I also think that what you need to change is not how the hash is computed. What you need to change is how ThumbnailPath is computed. Hence, you should use an interface like:

    public interface ThumbnailGenerator{ //give a mock for the ThumbnailGenerator at testing.
      public ThumbnailPath generatePath(Object argumentToUseInGeneration);
    }

instead of 

    public interface HashGenerator{
      public Object generateHash(Object argument);
    }

NOTE: In java, hash calculation is within the object itself because hash calculation depends on the object state. (You could pass an helper object in calculating the hash but the hash method is within the object).

